problem link : https://leetcode.com/problems/find-the-duplicate-number/description/

Intuition
Since the array has n+1 elements but every value lies in [1,n], at least one value must repeat. If we treat each index as a node and define the next node as nums[index], the array forms a linked-list-like graph. Because a value is duplicated, two different paths eventually merge, creating a cycle. The entrance of this cycle corresponds to the duplicate value. Therefore, we can use Floyd's Cycle Detection Algorithm to find the cycle entrance and return it as the duplicate number.

Approach
start with slow and fast both at 0
now as we know the cycle exists , we write loop condition while True:
move slow by one link and fast by two links in the linked list formed by i = arr[i] , when slow == high or meet , then take a pointer ptr and place it at 0 and slow remains at meeting point , move slow and ptr together when they meet , the number they meet at is duplicate number , return that .

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(n)
Floyd's Cycle Detection Algorithm consists of two linear phases:
Detect a meeting point inside the cycle.
Find the cycle entrance.
Each phase requires at most O(n) steps, resulting in an overall time complexity of O(n).

Space complexity:
O(1) Only a constant number of pointers are used, regardless of the input size.
Code
class Solution:
    def findDuplicate(self, nums: List[int]) -> int:
        slow = 0
        fast = 0
        while True:
            slow = nums[slow]
            fast = nums[fast]
            fast = nums[fast]
            if slow == fast:
                ptr = 0
                while slow != ptr:
                    slow = nums[slow]
                    ptr = nums[ptr]
                return slow
